# Insurance Platform — Senior UI Case Study Plan

Implementation guide for the ABC Insurance claims adjudication portal. Priorities: **architecture**, **performance**, and **code quality**. Follow the existing Nx monorepo layout; do not invent parallel folder conventions.

---

## Case Study Context

ABC Insurance is rebuilding a legacy claims system with a modern UI. The app integrates internal/external services for risk assessment and handles document-heavy workflows (email, SFTP, structured/unstructured data).

### Functional Requirements

| Area | Requirement |
|------|-------------|
| **Claims grid** | 20,000+ records; server-side sort/filter; row actions Edit / Delete / Assign; pagination or justified alternative (virtualization) |
| **RBAC** | Records and UI actions filtered by role; **backend = source of truth**, frontend = UX (show/hide/disable) |
| **Grid → workspace** | Row selection opens associated documents (150 MB–1 GB); smooth transition with loading/progress states |
| **Document workspace** | Efficient large-doc viewing; edit, split, merge, delete; page-level comments; annotations |

### Non-Functional Requirements

| Area | Requirement |
|------|-------------|
| **Performance** | Responsive UI; minimal re-renders; bounded memory for grid and document viewer |
| **Scalability** | Growing record volume, document size, concurrent users/operations |
| **UX** | Clear loading/progress; perceived performance; error recovery; cancel/retry for long-running jobs |
| **Reliability** | Consistent document state after split/merge/comment; graceful partial-failure handling |

### Evaluation Focus (document in README / architecture notes)

- **Architecture** — component boundaries, state management, data fetching/caching, API assumptions, authz/validation placement
- **Performance strategy** — 20k+ rows (server ops + virtualization); 1 GB docs (streaming, partial load, web workers, chunked ops)
- **Trade-offs** — pagination vs virtualization; client vs server processing; caching; optimistic vs pessimistic updates

